American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places, for example in Lincolnshire, Lancashire, Herefordshire, and North Yorkshire, all named with Old English <i>croft</i> ‘small arable enclosure (normally adjoining a house)’, or a topographic name for someone who lived by a croft, from Middle English <i>croft</i>.","English: possibly in some cases a variant of   Craft   2.","Americanized form of German, Danish, Swedish, or Jewish   Kraft  . Compare   Kroft   and   Craft  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Craft","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>craft</i> ‘skillful, clever, learned’.","English: habitational name from Croft in Leicestershire. See also   Croft  .","Americanized form of German, Danish, Swedish, or Jewish   Kraft  . See also   Croft  ."]},{"name":"Crate","meanings":["English (Hampshire and Surrey): from Middle English <i>crate</i> ‘hurdle, basket’, or occasionally perhaps from <i>crete</i> ‘cradle’, probably applied as a metonymic occupational name for a maker of such articles. Alternatively, sometimes perhaps a variant of   Croft   1."]},{"name":"Crofts","meanings":["English: variant of   Croft  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Groft","meanings":["English: perhaps an altered form of   Croft  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":5,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://e